 Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eyton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Eyton (Shrops) or Eaton (Cheshire, Leics, Staffs), or Eaton Bray (Beds), Cold Eaton or Long Eaton (Derbys)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ayton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Ayton (North Yorkshire) or Ayton (Berwickshire). The former is derived from Old Norse <i>á</i> ‘river, stream’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead’. The later takes its name from the River Eye (likely from Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":40,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":53,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":62,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Eyton was born about 1275, in Wildmore, Lincolnshire, England, his father, William de Eyton, was 28 and his mother, Lady Margery Matilda De Pedwardine, was 52. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Isabella Curzon. He died in 1345, in Dover, Kent, England, at the age of 71."},"et":{"Abt 1275–1345":"umbes 1275–1345","1275–1345":"1275–1345","1280–1320":"1280–1320","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1224–1292":"1224–1292","1275":"1275","1383":"1383","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1345":"1345","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","1320":"1320","estimated 1300":"umbes 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Wildmore, Lincolnshire, England":"Wildmore, Lincolnshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Wildmoors, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, Un